# QuestionnaireHelper — YAML authoring rules

This project is a generic client-side questionnaire app. Survey content lives entirely in YAML files loaded via `?yaml=<file>` URL parameter.

## Schema

```yaml
meta:
  title: TextValue          # required
  organization: TextValue   # optional
  description: TextValue    # optional

sections:                   # required, non-empty array
  - id: "1"                 # required, unique string
    title: TextValue        # required
    description: TextValue  # optional
    questions:              # required, non-empty array
      - id: "Q1.1"          # required, globally unique across ALL questions
        title: TextValue    # required
        context: TextValue  # optional — framing shown below the title
        prompts:            # optional — array of TextValue bullet points
          - TextValue

summary:                    # optional — rendered with a dark header
  title: TextValue          # required if present
  description: TextValue    # optional
  questions:
    - id: "S1"
      title: TextValue
```

## TextValue

```yaml
# Plain string:
title: "How do you rate the experience?"

# Bilingual object (triggers language switcher in the UI):
title:
  en: "How do you rate the experience?"
  zh: "您如何评价这次体验？"
```

Any ISO language key is valid. Use bilingual objects consistently — if one field is bilingual, make all fields bilingual.

## Rules

1. `meta.title` is required and non-empty.
2. `sections` must be a non-empty array.
3. Every `section.id` must be unique among sections.
4. Every `question.id` must be **globally unique** across all sections **and** the summary.
5. `prompts` must be an **array** (never a plain string).
6. The `summary` block is optional; omit it entirely if not needed.

## ID conventions

| Scope | Pattern | Examples |
|-------|---------|---------|
| Sections | sequential integers | `"1"`, `"2"`, `"3"` |
| Section questions | `Q<section>.<number>` | `"Q1.1"`, `"Q2.3"` |
| Summary questions | `S<number>` | `"S1"`, `"S2"` |

## Validation

Run `node -e "const v=require('./validator.js'); const d=require('js-yaml').load(require('fs').readFileSync('your-file.yaml','utf8')); console.log(v.validateYAML(d))"` to check a file, or open it in the browser — validation errors are shown inline.
